05896nam a22007335i 9780773564282DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735642827 a10.1515/97807735642822doi  a(DE-B1597)655976  a(OCoLC)732601089  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD1331.C2bW556 1994eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a971.3/591 aWilson, Catherine Anne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Lease on Life :bLandlords, Tenants, and Immigrants in Ireland and Canada /cCatherine Anne Wilson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Ethnic History ;v1700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tTables -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tLandlords -- tLord Mount Cashell: An Improving and Evangelical Landlord -- tHis Lordship’s Adventure Abroad -- tThe Famine and His Lordship’s Demise -- tMajor Maxwell’s Irish Estates: A New Kind of Management -- tMajor Maxwell’s Estate on Amherst Island -- tTenants -- tThe Ards Peninsula -- tThe Emigrants and Their Settlement on Amherst Island -- tWhat It Meant to be a Tenant on Amherst Island -- tConclusion -- tAmherst Island Immigrant Families from the Ards* -- tNotes -- tA Note on Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Part 1 Wilson reconstructs the family circumstances and estate management of two landlords, Stephen Moore, third earl of Mount Cashell, and Major Robert Perceval Maxwell. Each owned several estates in Ireland and the estate known as Amherst Island in Ontario. She examines how the management of these estates changed over time and highlights the differences between management in the north and south of Ireland, particularly in Counties Down, Antrim, and Cork. She looks at the form the landlord-tenant relationship took in the New World to determine whether tenancy arrangements in the New World offered landlords an opportunity to start afresh or, instead, were influenced by the traditions and financial circumstances of their Irish estates. The second part of the study follows more than one hundred tenant families who, between 1820 and 1860, migrated from the Ards Peninsula in County Down to Amherst Island, where they rented land from Mount Cashell and, later, from Maxwell. Wilson reveals what life was like in the United Parish of St Andrews, why families emigrated and rented on Amherst Island, and what it meant socially and economically to be a tenant in the New World, where most farmers were freeholders. Wilson sets her study firmly in the framework of British, Irish, and American writing on land tenure, and in this comparative context opens the discussion of tenancy among Canadians more widely than anyone has done heretofore. She concludes that both landlords and tenants were more successful in the New World. Wealth and land ownership might be slow in materializing, but the opportunity, the choices, and the attainment of security were all greater than they had been in Ireland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aColonisation intérieurexHistoirex19e sièclexOntarioxAmherst Island. 0aImmigrantsxHistoirex19e sièclexOntarioxAmherst Island. 0aImmigrantsxHistoryx19th centuryxOntarioxAmherst Island. 0aImmigrantszOntariozAmherst IslandxHistoryy19th century. 0aIrishxHistoryx19th centuryxOntarioxAmherst Island. 0aIrishzOntariozAmherst IslandxHistoryy19th century. 0aIrlandaisxHistoirex19e sièclexOntarioxAmherst Island. 0aLand settlementxHistoryx19th centuryxOntarioxAmherst Island. 0aLand settlementzOn